# OPERATING MODEL

> **The operational model that governs how the OpenCode AI Engineering Kit makes decisions, executes work, and evolves software systems.**

---

# Purpose

The OpenCode AI Engineering Kit is not a collection of prompts.

It is an engineering operating system.

Its purpose is to coordinate specialized AI components that work together through clearly defined responsibilities, shared artifacts, and continuous architectural governance.

This document defines the operational rules that every Agent, Skill, MCP integration, and workflow must follow.

---

# Operational Philosophy

The framework follows five fundamental principles:

1. Strategy is separated from execution.
2. Skills never make architectural decisions.
3. All collaboration occurs through shared artifacts.
4. Every execution updates the project's engineering knowledge.
5. Architecture is continuously verified.

---

# Layers

The framework is organized into five logical layers.

```
User
    │
    ▼
Chief Architect
    │
    ▼
Execution Planner
    │
    ▼
Specialized Skills
    │
    ▼
Engineering Artifacts
```

Each layer has a single responsibility.

---

# Layer 1 — User

The user defines goals.

Examples:

* Improve performance
* Fix a bug
* Optimize the RAG
* Add a new feature
* Refactor authentication

The user never defines implementation details.

---

# Layer 2 — Chief Architect

The Chief Architect is the strategic decision maker.

Responsibilities include:

* understanding objectives
* defining priorities
* protecting architectural integrity
* deciding when work is complete
* selecting the appropriate execution strategy

The Chief Architect does **not** modify source code.

The Chief Architect does **not** produce diagrams.

The Chief Architect does **not** implement features.

Its role is coordination.

---

# Layer 3 — Execution Planner

The Execution Planner transforms strategic objectives into executable engineering plans.

Responsibilities include:

* selecting Skills
* defining execution order
* identifying dependencies
* estimating impact
* validating prerequisites
* coordinating execution loops

The planner is responsible for orchestration.

It never modifies project artifacts directly.

---

# Layer 4 — Specialized Skills

Skills perform engineering work.

Each Skill owns exactly one responsibility.

Examples:

* Architecture
* Documentation
* Improve
* Review
* Testing
* Performance
* Security
* RAG Auditor
* Knowledge Manager

Skills should never duplicate responsibilities.

Skills should never coordinate other Skills.

Skills should never redefine project priorities.

---

# Layer 5 — Engineering Artifacts

Artifacts represent the shared engineering knowledge of the project.

Examples include:

* architecture.md
* roadmap.md
* technical-debt.md
* ADRs
* project-state.yaml
* Draw.io diagrams
* performance reports
* security reports

Artifacts are the primary communication mechanism between Skills.

No Skill should rely on hidden context from previous executions.

---

# Communication Model

The framework follows an artifact-driven architecture.

```
Skill

↓

Engineering Artifact

↓

Next Skill
```

Skills never communicate directly.

This guarantees loose coupling and reproducible workflows.

---

# Decision Model

Only the Chief Architect may make architectural decisions.

Execution Planner may sequence work.

Skills may only execute work.

Documentation reflects completed work.

Review validates completed work.

---

# Execution Cycle

Every engineering task follows the same lifecycle.

```
Understand

↓

Plan

↓

Analyze

↓

Execute

↓

Validate

↓

Document

↓

Review

↓

Persist Knowledge

↓

Finish
```

No phase may be skipped.

---

# Incremental Engineering

Large modifications increase project risk.

The framework therefore prefers:

* small pull requests
* isolated improvements
* incremental refactoring
* continuous verification
* measurable progress

Each execution should improve only one engineering concern whenever possible.

---

# Shared Knowledge

Engineering knowledge must persist beyond individual AI conversations.

Persistent knowledge includes:

* architectural documentation
* engineering decisions
* project state
* technical debt
* diagrams
* reports
* roadmaps

The framework should rely on persistent artifacts before relying on language model memory.

---

# Project State

The current project state is represented by a structured artifact.

This state includes:

* current architecture version
* current roadmap
* pending improvements
* completed work
* active priorities
* latest review
* latest diagrams
* engineering metrics

The Project State becomes the operational memory of the framework.

---

# Continuous Documentation

Documentation is generated continuously.

There is no separate documentation phase.

Every structural modification updates:

* documentation
* diagrams
* architecture decisions
* project state

Documentation is treated as production code.

---

# Continuous Architecture

Architecture is continuously inspected.

Every execution should answer:

* Does this reduce complexity?
* Does this improve maintainability?
* Does this reduce coupling?
* Does this increase cohesion?
* Does this preserve architectural consistency?

If the answer is no, the execution should be reconsidered.

---

# Quality Gates

Before work is considered complete, the following gates must pass:

* Architecture Review
* Documentation Updated
* Project State Updated
* Tests Passed
* Draw.io Updated (when applicable)
* ADR Updated (when applicable)

Incomplete work is never considered finished.

---

# Extensibility

New Skills should be added without modifying existing Skills.

This is achieved through:

* shared artifacts
* standardized contracts
* isolated responsibilities
* orchestration through the Execution Planner

The framework should remain open for extension and closed for modification.

---

# Guiding Rule

Every execution must leave the project in a better engineering state than it was before.

Improvement is measured not only by new functionality, but also by increased architectural quality, better documentation, reduced technical debt, and preserved engineering knowledge.

The framework exists to ensure that AI contributes to the long-term evolution of software systems with consistency, transparency, and engineering discipline.
